==Themes==

''Eraserhead''{{'s}} sound design has been seen as one of its defining elements. Although the film features several hallmark visuals<U+2014>the deformed infant and the sprawling industrial setting<U+2014>these are matched by their accompanying sounds, with the "incessant mewling" and "evocative aural landscape" paired with these respectively.<ref name="scenic route">{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/david-lynch-shows-how-audio-can-be-creepier-than-a,73926/ |title=David Lynch shows how audio can be creepier than any image in Eraserhead |publisher=''[[The A.V. Club]]'' |first=Mike |last=D'Angelo |date=May 14, 2012 |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> The film features several constantly-present industrial sounds, providing low-level background noise in every scene. The effect of this is to provide a "threatening" and "unnerving" atmosphere, which has since been imitated in works such as [[David Fincher]]'s 1995 thriller ''[[Seven (film)|Seven]]'' and the [[Coen brothers]]' 1991 comedy ''[[Barton Fink]]''.<ref name="scenic route"/> The constant low-level noise has been seen as perhaps being a product of Henry Spencer's imagination, with the soundtrack being "ruthlessly negligent of the difference between dream and reality".{{sfn|Wierzbicki|2012|p=182}} The film also begins a trend within Lynch's work of relating [[diegesis|diegetic]] music to dreams, with the Lady in the Radiator singing "In Heaven" during Spencer's extended dream sequence. This is also seen in "Episode 2" of ''Twin Peaks'', with diegetic music carrying over from a character's dream to his waking thoughts; and in 1986's ''[[Blue Velvet (film)|Blue Velvet]]'', with the focus given to [[Roy Orbison]]'s "[[In Dreams (song)|In Dreams]]".{{sfn|Wierzbicki|2012|p=182}}

The film has also been noted for its strong sexual themes. Opening with an image of conception, the film then portrays Henry Spencer as a character both terrified of, and fascinated by sex. The recurring images of sperm-like creatures, including the child, are a constant presence during the film's sex scenes; while the apparent "[[girl next door]]" appeal of the Lady in the Radiator is thrown aside during her musical number as she begins to violently smash Spencer's sperm creatures and aggressively meets his gaze.{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=32}} David J. Skal, in his book ''The Monster Show: A Cultural History of Horror'', has described the film as "depict[ing] human reproduction as a desolate freak show, an occupation fit only for the damned". Skal also posits a different characterization of the Lady in the Radiator, describing her as "desperately eager for an unseen audience's approval".{{sfn|Skal|2001|p=298}} In his book ''David Lynch Decoded'', Mark Allyn Stewart proposes that the Lady in the Radiator is in fact Spencer's [[subconscious]], a manifestation of his own urge to kill his child, who embraces him after the deed as if to say he has done the right thing.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=7}}

As a character, Spencer has been seen as an [[everyman]] figure, his blank expression and plain dress keeping him a simple archetype.{{sfn|Olson|2008|p=62}} Spencer displays a [[pacifism|pacifistic]] and [[fatalism|fatalistic]] inactivity throughout the film, simply allowing events to unfold around him without taking control for himself. This passive behavior culminates in his sole act of instigation at the film's climax, his apparent act of infanticide driven by his life of being domineered and controlled. Spencer's inactivity has also been seen as a precursor to Lynch's 1983<U+2013>1992 comic strip ''[[The Angriest Dog in the World]]''.{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=33}}

==Release==

===Box office===

''Eraserhead'' premi<U+00E8>red at the [[Filmex]] film festival in [[Los Angeles]], on March 19, 1977.{{sfn|Hoberman|Rosenbaum|1991|p=215}} On its opening night, the film was attended by twenty-five people; and twenty-four the following night. However, [[Ben Barenholtz]], head of distributor [[Libra Films International]], persuaded local theater Cinema Village to run the film as a midnight feature, where it continued to be screened for a full year. After this, it ran for ninety-nine weeks at New York's [[IFC Center|Waverly Cinema]], as well as enjoying a year-long midnight run at [[San Francisco]]'s [[Roxie Theater]] from 1978 to 1979, and a three-year tenure at Los Angeles' [[Nuart Theatre]] between 1978 and 1981.{{sfn|Hoberman|Rosenbaum|1991|p=220}} The film went on to gross [[United States dollar|$]]7,000,000 in the United States.<ref name="numbers">{{cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1977/0ERHE.php |title=Eraserhead <U+2013> Box Office Data, DVD Sales, Movie News, Cast Information |publisher=The Numbers |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> ''Eraserhead'' was also screened as part of the 1978 [[BFI London Film Festival]],<ref name="regus">{{cite web |url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/event/2879 |title=BFI {{!}} Film & TV Database {{!}} 22nd |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref> and the 1986 [[Telluride Film Festival]].<ref name="rovi"/>

===Home media===

''Eraserhead'' was first released on [[VHS]] on August 7, 1982 by [[Columbia Pictures]].<ref name="vhs release">{{cite journal |date=August 7, 1982 |title=New Video Releases |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=94 |issue=31 |page=34 |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |issn= 0006-2510 |url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FiQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT33&lpg=PT33&dq=eraserhead+vhs&source=bl&ots=EcGpoKQHet&sig=v39QgqmQdAYiSoPyk3Ns2yXs9kw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7H81ULG3O8j80QXx-YHwDA&ved=0CFUQuwUwBw#v=onepage&q=eraserhead%20vhs&f=false |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> The film was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] by [[Umbrella Entertainment]] in Australia, with the former being released on August 1, 2009,<ref name="umbrella dvd">{{cite web |url=http://www.umbrellaent.com.au/p-2084-eraserhead.aspx |title=Umbrella Entertainment <U+2013> Eraserhead (DVD) |publisher=[[Umbrella Entertainment]] |accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref> and the latter on May 9, 2012.<ref name="umbrella blu">{{cite web |url=http://www.umbrellaent.com.au/p-3018-eraserhead-blu-ray.aspx |title=Umbrella Entertainment <U+2013> Eraserhead (Blu-Ray) |publisher=[[Umbrella Entertainment]] |accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref> Both of the Umbrella Entertainment releases include an 85-minute feature on the making of the film.<ref name="umbrella dvd"/><ref name="umbrella blu"/> Other home media releases of the film include DVD releases by [[Universal Pictures]] in North America in 2001, Subversive Entertainment in 2006, and Scanbox Entertainment in 2008.<ref name="rovi"/>

==Reception==

[[File:Luis bunuel 1920.jpg|right|upright|thumb|alt=A black-and-white photograph of a man in a suit|''Eraserhead'' has been compared to the films of Spanish director [[Luis Bu<U+00F1>uel]].]]

Upon ''Eraserhead''{{'s}} release, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' offered a negative review of the film, calling it "a sickening bad-taste exercise".<ref name="variety"/> The review expressed incredulity over the film's long gestation, and described its finale as "unwatchable".<ref name="variety">{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117790719/ |title=Variety Reviews <U+2013> Eraserhead <U+2013> Film Reviews <U+2013> <U+2013> Review by Variety Staff |publisher=''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' |year=1977 |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> Writing in 1984, Lloyd Rose of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' felt that ''Eraserhead'' demonstrated that Lynch was "one of the most unalloyed surrealists ever to work in the movies".<ref name="atlantic">{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-211473134.html |title=Tumoresque: the films of David Lynch |first=Lloyd |last=Rose |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=October 1, 1984 |accessdate=August 22, 2012}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Rose described the film as being intensely personal, finding that unlike previous surrealist films such as Luis Bu<U+00F1>uel's 1929 work ''[[Un Chien Andalou]]'' or 1930's ''[[L'Age d'Or]]'', Lynch's imagery "isn't reaching out to us from his films; we're sinking into them".<ref name="atlantic"/> In a 1993 review for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', Michael Wilmington described ''Eraserhead'' as "one of a kind".<ref name="tribune">{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-11-19/entertainment/9311190246_1_jack-nance-henry-spencer-star |title=Eraserhead Makes Its Mark As A Monument To Alienation |first=Michael |last=Wilmington |date=November 19, 1993 |publisher=''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' |accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref> Wilmington felt that the film's "intensity" and "nightmare clarity" were a result of Lynch's attention to detail in creating it, noting his involvement in so many roles during its production.<ref name="tribune"/>

Modern critical opinion of the film is widely positive. ''Eraserhead'' holds an average rating of 90% on [[review aggregator|review aggregation]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], representing the distillation of forty-two reviews.<ref name="rotten">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/eraserhead/ |title=Eraserhead |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine, Steve Beard rated the film five stars out of five. Beard felt that the film was "a lot more radical and enjoyable than [Lynch's] later Hollywood efforts", and highlighted its mix of surrealist [[body horror]] and [[black humor|black comedy]].<ref name="empire">{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=14647 |title=Empire's Eraserhead Movie Review |first=Steve |last=Beard |publisher=''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> [[BBC]]'s Almar Haflidason awarded ''Eraserhead'' three stars out of five, describing it as "an unremarkable feat by [Lynch's] later standards".<ref name="bbc">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/01/16/eraserhead_1977_review.shtml |title=BBC <U+2013> Films <U+2013> review <U+2013> Eraserhead |first=Almar |last=Haflidason |date=January 16, 2001 |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> Haflidason felt that the film was a "crude assemblage of ideas", adding that it is "so consumed with surreal imagery that there are almost limitless possibilities to read personal theories into it"; the reviewer's own take on these themes were that it represented a fear of personal commitment and featured "a strong sexual undercurrent".<ref name="bbc"/> A review by [[Film4]] rated ''Eraserhead'' five stars out of five, describing it as "by turns beautiful, annoying, funny, exasperating and repellent, but always bristling with a nervous energy".<ref name="film4">{{cite web |url=http://www.film4.com/reviews/1977/eraserhead |title=Eraserhead (1977) <U+2013> Film Review |publisher=[[Film4]] |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> The Film4 review felt that ''Eraserhead'' was unlike most films released to that point, save for the collaborations between [[Luis Bu<U+00F1>uel]] and [[Salvador Dal<U+00ED>]]; however, Lynch denies having seen any of these films before creating ''Eraserhead''.<ref name="film4"/> Writing for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Nathan Lee praised the film's use of sound, writing "to see the film means nothing<U+2014>one must also ''hear'' it".<ref name="village">{{cite web |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2007-01-09/film/david-lynch-made-a-man-out-of-me/ |title=David Lynch Made a Man Out of Me |publisher=''[[The Village Voice]]'' |first=Nathan |last=Lee |date=January 9, 2007 |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref> Lee described the film's sound design as "an intergalactic seashell cocked to the ears of an [[LSD|acid-tripping]] gargantua".<ref name="village"/>

''[[The Guardian]]''{{'s}} Peter Bradshaw similarly lauded the film, awarding it another five stars out of five. Bradshaw described the film as "beautiful and strange, with its profoundly disturbing ambient sound design of industrial groaning, as if filmed inside some collapsing factory or gigantic dying organism".<ref name="guardian">{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2008/sep/12/horror1?INTCMP=SRCH |title=Film review: Eraserhead {{!}} Film |publisher=''[[The Guardian]]'' |first=Peter |last=Bradshaw |date=September 12, 2008 |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> Bradshaw highlighted the film's body horror elements, comparing it to [[Ridley Scott]]'s 1979 film ''[[Alien (film)|Alien]]''.<ref name="guardian"/> Keith Phipps, writing for [[AllRovi]], also gave the film a rating of five stars out of five; Phipps highlighted the disturbing sound design of the film and described it as "an open metaphor".<ref name="rovi">{{cite web |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/eraserhead-v15947 |title=Eraserhead <U+2013> Review |first=Keith |last=Phipps |work=[[Allmovie]] |publisher=[[AllRovi]] |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> Phipps felt that ''Eraserhead'' "sets up the obsessions that would follow [Lynch] through his career", adding his belief that the film's surrealism enhanced the understanding of the director's later films.<ref name="rovi"/> In an article for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', film-maker [[Marc Evans]] has described the film as an inspiration on his own work, praising both the sound design and Lynch's ability "to make the ordinary seem so odd".<ref name="telegraph">{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3583763/Film-makers-on-film-Marc-Evans.html |title=Film makers on film: Marc Evans |first1=Marc |last1=Evans |authorlink1=Marc Evans |first2=Mark |last2=Monahan |publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' |date=October 5, 2002 |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> A review of the film in the same newspaper compared it to the works of Irish playwright [[Samuel Beckett]], describing it as a chaotic parody of family life.<ref name="telegraph2">{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/3562417/DVD-reviews-Charley-Varrick-Iron-Man-Eraserhead-The-Short-Films-of-David-Lynch-Festen-10th-Anniversary-Edition.html |title=DVD reviews: Charley Varrick, Iron Man, Eraserhead, The Short Films of David Lynch, Festen 10th Anniversary Edition |first=David |last=Cheal  |publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' |date=October 22, 2008 |accessdate=August 31, 2012}}</ref> Manohla Dargis, writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', described the film as "less a straight story than a surrealistic assemblage".<ref name="nyt rev">{{cite web |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/07/movies/07eras.html?_r=1&scp=3&sq=eraserhead&st=cse |title=Distorted, Distorting and All-Too Human |first=Manohla |last=Dargis |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |date=December 7, 2007 |accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref> Dargis felt that the film's imagery evoked the paintings of [[Francis Bacon]] and the [[Georges Franju]] 1949 documentary ''[[Blood of the Beasts]]''.<ref name="nyt rev"/> ''[[Film Threat]]''{{'s}} Phil Hall called ''Eraserhead'' "Lynch at his best", believing that the director's subsequent output failed to live up to it.<ref name="threat">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/8630/ |title=Film Threat <U+2013> Eraserhead (DVD) |first=Phil |last=Hall |publisher=''[[Film Threat]]'' |date=February 10, 2006 |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref> Hall highlighted the film's soundtrack and Nance's "[[Charlie Chaplin|Chaplinesque]]" physical comedy as the film's stand-out elements.<ref name="threat"/>

==Legacy==

In 2004, ''Eraserhead'' was selected for preservation in the [[National Film Registry]] by the United States [[Library of Congress]]. Selection for the Registry is based on a film being deemed "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant".<ref name="2004Add">{{cite press release|title=Films Added to National Film Registry for 2004|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|date=December 28, 2004|url=http://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2004/04-215.html|accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> The film was one of the subjects featured in the 2005 documentary ''[[Midnight Movies: From the Margin to the Mainstream]]'', which charted the rise of the [[midnight movie]] phenomenon in the late 1960s and 1970s; Lynch took part in the documentary through a series of interviews.<ref name="margin">{{cite web |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/midnight-movies-from-the-margin-to-the-mainstream-v327348 |title=Midnight Movies: From the Margin to the Mainstream <U+2013> Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |work=[[Allmovie]] |publisher=[[AllRovi]] |first=Nathan |last=Southern |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> In 2010, the [[Online Film Critics Society]] compiled a list of the 100 best directorial d<U+00E9>buts, listing what they felt were the best first-time feature films by noted directors. ''Eraserhead'' placed second in the poll, coming behind [[Orson Welles]]' 1941 film ''[[Citizen Kane]]''.<ref name="online100">{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/online-critics-post-top-100-directorial-debuts-of-alltime-2099107.html?origin=internalSearch |title=Online critics post top 100 directorial debuts of all-time |publisher=''[[The Independent]]'' |date=October 6, 2010 |accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref>

Lynch would end up collaborating with most of the cast and crew of ''Eraserhead'' again on his later films. Frederick Elmes served as cinematographer on ''Blue Velvet'',{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=53}} 1988's ''The Cowboy and the Frenchman'', and 1990's ''[[Wild at Heart (film)|Wild at Heart]]'';{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=62<U+2013>63}} while Alan Splet provided sound design for ''The Elephant Man'', ''Dune'' and ''Blue Velvet''.<ref name="splet rovi">{{cite web |url=http://www.allrovi.com/name/alan-splet-p112354 |title=Alan Splet <U+2013> Move and Film Biography and Filmography |work=[[Allmovie]] |publisher=[[AllRovi]] |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> Jack Fisk later directed episodes of Lynch's 1992 television series ''[[On the Air (TV series)|On the Air]]'',{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=87}} and worked as a production designer on 2001's ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]'' and 1999's ''[[The Straight Story]]''.<ref name="fisk rovi">{{cite web |url=http://www.allrovi.com/name/jack-p89912 |title=Jack Fisk <U+2013> Move and Film Biography and Filmography |work=[[Allmovie]] |publisher=[[AllRovi]] |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> Coulson and Nance both appeared in ''Twin Peaks'',{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=69}} with Nance making further appearances in ''Dune'',{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=46}} ''Blue Velvet'',{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=53}} ''Wild at Heart'',{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=63}} and 1997's ''[[Lost Highway (film)|Lost Highway]]''.{{sfn|Odell|Le Blanc|2007|p=95}}

Following the release of ''Eraserhead'', Lynch next attempted to find funding for his next project, ''[[Ronnie Rocket]]'', a film "about electricity and a three-foot guy with red hair".{{sfn|Rodley|Lynch|2005|p=91}} Lynch met film producer met [[Stuart Cornfeld]] during this time. Cornfeld had enjoyed ''Eraserhead'' and was interested in producing ''Ronnie Rocket''; Cornfeld was working for [[Mel Brooks]] and [[List of Brooksfilms productions|Brooksfilms]] at the time, and when the two realized that ''Ronnie Rocket'' was unlikely to find sufficient financing to be produced, Lynch asked to see some already-written scripts to work from for his next film instead. Cornfeld found four scripts he felt Lynch would be interested in, but on hearing the name of the first, the director decided his next project would be ''The Elephant Man''.{{sfn|Rodley|Lynch|2005|p=92}}

''Eraserhead'' served as an influence on [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s 1980 film ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]''; Kubrick reportedly screened the film for the cast and crew to "put them in the mood" he wanted to achieve for the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/david-lynch/eraserhead-the-short-films-of-david-lynch-review|title=Eraserhead, The Short Films Of David Lynch|last=Roberts|first=Chris|work=uncut.co.uk|accessdate=August 26, 2012}}</ref> ''Eraserhead'' is also credited with influencing the 1990 Japanese cyberpunk film ''[[Tetsuo: The Iron Man]]'', the experimental 1990 horror film ''[[Begotten]]'' and [[Darren Aronofsky]]'s 1998 directorial debut ''[[Pi (film)|Pi]]''.{{sfn|Harper|2007|p=140}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.film.com/movies/whats-the-big-deal-eraserhead-1977|title=What's the big deal?: Eraserhead (1977)|last=Snider|first=Eric D.|work=film.com|accessdate=August 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>Vaughan, Robin. "''Pi'' movie adds up to stimulating analysis." ''[[The Boston Herald]]''. October 4, 2004.</ref>

